g.text: Chromosome of the sequence. E.g. "1" for chromosome 1. Note that value of `chromosome` is not limited to a human's chromosomes, as the sequence can be from other species such as Tuberculosischromosome : string 1..1
0-based location start position (inclusive) of the sequencestartPosition : integer 1..1
0-based end location (exclusive) of the sequenceendPosition : integer 1..1
Direction of the strand. Forward means the sequence is in 5'-3' direction, reverse otherwisedirection : code 0..1 « Direction of a sequenceStrandDirection »

Extended CIGAR string for aligning the sequence with reference bases. See detailed documentation [here](http://support.illumina.com/help/SequencingAnalysisWorkflow/Content/Vault/Informatics/Sequencing_Analysis/CASAVA/swSEQ_mCA_ExtendedCIGARFormat.htm)cigar : string 0..1
Tissue sample from which molecules encoded by the sequence are extractedsample : code 0..1 « Type of the sample used to determine a seauenceSampleType »
Lab where the sequence is determinedlab : Reference(DiagnosticOrder) 0..1
Whom the sequence is determined for. In a prenatal sequencing test, the patient being referenced is the birthgiverpatient : Reference(Patient) 1..1

Species of the organism whom the sequence belongs to. The species is not limited to Homo sapiens. E.g. the sequence can be a DNA sequence of a bacteriaspecies : CodeableConcept 1..1 « Species of the organism to whom the sequence belongs toSNOMED CT Codes for species »
Quantity of molecule encoded by the sequence presenting in the samplequantity : Quantity 0..1
Genome assembly used to align the sequencegenomeBuild : string 0..1
Type of the sequence. E.g. DNAtype : code 1..1 « Type of a sequenceSequenceType »
Reference bases of the sequencereferenceSequence : string 0..1
Observed bases of the sequenceobservedSequence : string 1..1
Alterantive name of the sequence -- e.g. gene covered by the sequence, exome region in which the sequence is located, rsid of the sequence if it's a SNP, etcname : CodeableConcept 0..*
